    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-02T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-02T20:00:00-05:00" n="624"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d624">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115N27/13a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-02T20:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 2, 1915, 8 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1770. The evidence thus far furnished indicates that <hi rend="italic"
                        >Nebraskan</hi> was struck by a torpedo on evening of May 25.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d624fn1">The full text of depositions and reports forwarded by the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain May 28 and June 2, is printed in <hi
                            rend="italic">Diplomatic Correspondence with Belligerent Governments
                            relating to Neutral Rights and Duties</hi>, Department of State,
                        European War No. 4, May 18, 1918, pp. 229–34; reprinted in the <hi
                            rend="italic">American Journal of International Law</hi>, vol. 11,
                        Special Supplement, pp. 82–89.</note> Please inquire whether the German
                    Government has any report of attack on this vessel. It was an American vessel
                    leaving Liverpool.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
